==Development==
''The Rocky Horror Show'' was published and developed by [[CRL Group]], having made previously licensed games such as [[The War of the Worlds (1984 video game)|''The War of the Worlds'']]. In 1984, negotiations by CRL were made to obtain the rights to make a computer game on the property.<ref name="PCW">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Popular Computing Weekly]]|title=Rocky Horror Picture Show game from CRL|date=8 November 1984|page=5|url=https://archive.org/stream/popular-computing-weekly-1984-11-08/PopularComputing_Weekly_Issue_1984-11-08#page/n3/mode/2up}}</ref> CRL's [[CEO]] Clem Chambers claimed in an interview with ''[[GamesTM]]'' that the rights holder for the property approached the company after being impressed by their work with ''The War of the Worlds''.<ref>{{cite interview|url=https://www.gamestm.co.uk/interviews/in-converation-with-clem-chambers/|title=In converation with Clem Chambers|author=GamesTM Staff|work=[[GamesTM]]|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> Chambers stated he wanted to base the game on the environments of the stage show instead of "the elements of dubious taste in the show itself".<ref name="PCW"/>

''Rocky Horror''{{'}}s creator [[Richard O'Brien]] did not have much involvement with making the game, due to being "terrified of technology". Ian Ellery, a fan of ''Rocky Horror'', was the game's programmer.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Your Computer (British magazine)|Your Computer]]|title=Rocky Horror - A Small Scream|page=23|volume=5|number=3|date=March 1985|url=https://archive.org/stream/your-computer-magazine-1985-03/YourComputer_1985_03#page/n21/mode/2up/search/rocky}}</ref>

==Release==
Upon release the game came with a glossy colour fold-out poster and a sticker for the Spectrum, Amstrad and Commodore.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://ia800604.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/1/items/World_of_Spectrum_June_2017_Mirror/World%20of%20Spectrum%20June%202017%20Mirror.zip&file=World%20of%20Spectrum%20June%202017%20Mirror/sinclair/games-extras/RockyHorrorShowThe_Poster.png/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show CRL Poster }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://ia800604.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/1/items/World_of_Spectrum_June_2017_Mirror/World%20of%20Spectrum%20June%202017%20Mirror.zip&file=World%20of%20Spectrum%20June%202017%20Mirror/sinclair/games-extras/RockyHorrorShowThe_WindowSticker.png/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show CRL Sticker }}</ref>

There were two versions of the game released on the ZX Spectrum, with the standard 48k release in 1985 followed by an upgraded version for the 128k Spectrum in 1986.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.uvlist.net/game-261806-The+Rocky+Horror+Show/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show Spectrum 128 | date=Dec 2021 }}</ref>

Only the Spectrum and Amstrad versions feature a start up screen where the character Riff Raff dances "The Time Warp" alongside the lyrics.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thekingofgrabs.com/2019/03/21/the-rocky-horror-show-zx-spectrum/#jp-carousel-54535/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show Spectrum start up screen | date=Mar 2019 }}</ref>

The Commodore meanwhile had three separate releases.  The original C64 game was a straight ZX Spectrum port in 1985 (with different sprites), while an alternative C64 version was released in America by [[Electric_Dreams_Software|Electric Dreams]] in 1986 and featured entirely different graphics than the CRL version.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lemon64.com/game/rocky-horror-show-us | title=The Rocky Horror Show US Version | date=Feb 2023 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/26227/the-rocky-horror-show/cover/group-29669/cover-80332/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show US cover by Electric Dreams | date=Feb 2023 }}</ref> A completely reworked version was released by CRL in 1986 for the C128 with improved graphics, more detailed characters and more colourful backgrounds and new locations.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/26227/the-rocky-horror-show/screenshots/c128/582660/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show C128 | date=Sep 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gb64.com/oldsite/gameofweek/4/gotw_rockyhorrorshow.htm/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show C64 & C128 | date=Apr 2002 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.commodoreplus.org/2011/05/rocky-horror-show-64-128.html/ | title=The Rocky Horror Show 64/128 | date=May 2011 }}</ref>

